My Meme

Memes are well know for being funny and many time they become viral. I thought my meme will be a good choice because it can be funny and also give to people a good topic to talk about. For example, how we might not be taking care of ourselves or how some people get a lot of surgeries and cosmetic procedures to look more appealing in the media.

My Meme

library(magick)
library(tidyverse)

# Building the head text

top_text <- image_blank(width = 825, 
                        height = 125, 
                        color = "#000000") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "You are not Ugly",
                 color = "#FFFFFF",
                 size = 80,
                 font = "Impact",
                 gravity = "center")

# Building the center image

young_Tom <- image_read("https://qph.cf2.quoracdn.net/main-qimg-6b412fa3348ad055237be35bbdade1cc-lq") %>%
  image_scale(330)

Old_Tom <- image_read("https://cdn.fansshare.com/pictures/tomcruise/best-actor-tom-cruise-face-photo-871606198.jpg") %>%
  image_scale(495)
middle_vector <- c(young_Tom,Old_Tom)

middle_row <- image_append(middle_vector)

# Building the bottom text

lower_text <- image_blank(width = 825, 
                       height = 125, 
                       color = "#000000") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "You are just Poor",
                 color = "#FFFFFF",
                 size = 80,
                 font = "Impact",
                 gravity = "center")

# putting everything togheter

meme <-c(top_text, middle_row, lower_text) %>%
  image_append(stack = TRUE) %>%
  image_scale(825)

# Saving the meme as .png

image_write(meme, "my_meme.png")

My Animated GIF

A gif can be a good detail to send to people on their birthday. I created a gif which keep people engage to discover their greetings in the end. I used a collection of independent images that together tells an story.

My Animated GIF

library(magick)
library(tidyverse)

# creating each frame
frame1 <- image_read(path = "image_1.jpg")%>%
  image_scale(600) 
  image_crop(frame1, "100x150+50")
frame2 <- image_read(path = "image_2.jpg")%>%
  image_scale(600) 
frame3 <- image_read(path = "image_3.jpg")%>%
  image_scale(600) 
frame4 <- image_read(path = "image_4.jpg")%>%
  image_scale(600) 

# creating frame with word Happy
frame5 <- image_read(path = "image_5.jpg")%>%
  image_scale(600) %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Happy", size = 50, gravity = "South")
frame6 <- image_read(path = "image_6.jpg")%>%
  image_scale(600) %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Happy", size = 50, gravity = "South")

# creating frame with word Happy Birthday
frame7 <- image_read(path = "image_7.jpg")%>%
  image_scale(600) %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Happy Birthday!", size = 50, gravity = "South")
frame8 <- image_read(path = "image_8.jpg")%>%
  image_scale(600) %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Happy Birthday!", size = 50, gravity = "South")
frame9 <- image_read(path = "image_8.jpg")%>%
  image_scale(600) %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Happy Birthday!", size = 50, gravity = "South")
frame10 <- image_read(path = "image_8.jpg")%>%
  image_scale(600) %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Happy Birthday!", size = 50, gravity = "South")


# putting the frames in order using a vector
frames <- c(frame1,frame2,frame3,frame4,frame5,frame6,frame7,frame8,frame9,frame10)

# creating an animation
Happy_Birthday <- image_animate(frames, fps = 1.25)

# saving the animation as a .gif
image_write(Happy_Birthday, "Happy_Birthday.gif")

Note that the echo = FALSE parameter was added to the code chunk to prevent printing of the R code that generated the plot.
